      "rotationTime": "Rotation Time",
      "dps": "DPS",
      "noData": "No damage data available. Add actions to the timeline first.",
      "contributionByOperator": "Contribution by Operator",
      "lmdiModeStacks": "By Stacks",
      "lmdiModeStacksTip": "Breach, electrification, and corrosion contribution are split between the trigger and the infliction stack providers.",
      "lmdiModeApplier": "By Applier",
      "lmdiModeApplierTip": "Breach, electrification, and corrosion contribution go entirely to the operator who triggered the reaction.",
      "damage": "Damage",
      "buff": "Buff",
      "warning": "Damage analysis is for team optimization only. Please do not use it to attack others.",
      "faqTitle": "FAQ",
      "faq1Q": "Why is the damage different from the game?",
      "faq1A": "The simulation strictly follows a \"Hit before Effect\" rule: damage does NOT benefit from effects it applies, but DOES benefit from effects even if it consumes them. This is not always how the game works - try testing with Chen Qianyu's Talent 1.\n\nAdditionally, in-game numbers are rounded while the underlying data is non-integer. The simulation rounds everything down.\n\nIt's just a simulation.",
      "faq2Q": "What are the limitations of the damage calculation?",
      "faq2A": "There is no good way to implement \"On Crit\" effects in a static analysis. All \"On Crit\" triggers currently use \"On Hit\" instead, so calculated damage may be slightly higher than actual.",
      "faq3Q": "How is contribution calculated?",
      "faq3A": "LMDI (Logarithmic Mean Divisia Index).\nSince Endfield's damage formula is entirely multiplicative, LMDI can decompose each hit's damage into per-operator contributions with zero residual.\nInstead of vague statements like \"this Support roughly boosts total damage by 10%\", it tells you directly: \"out of 120k total damage, the Support contributed 12k.\" This makes it highly practical for comparing team compositions.\nFor arts and physical reactions, their damage and effect are attributed by each operator's infliction and vulnerability stack contributions.\nFor stagger, the 30% stagger multiplier bonus is attributed by each operator's stagger contributions.",
      "faq4Q": "Who is the most complicated operator?",
      "faq4A": "Pogranichnik."
    },
